r. The telegraph\nand cable companlea have entered\nenthusiastically Into the project an?\nUnci Sam will likely reach more\npeople with hla greeting than ever\nbefore.\nNew Vear'a fire In Iondon.\n-Bpeclal to Dally Panhandle.\nLondon, Dec. 31. The new year\nwill be welcomed with great' enthu\nsiasm, la London and with all the cus.\ntomary manifestations of good fel\nlowship. Especially notable, will be\nthe festivities at the famou Clar\nldge', which wU markq tho cen\ntenary of thl 'hotel. Claiidge's has\nbad an eventful history, having been\nfounded Jan. 1, 1X08, as the Hotel\nMovart. About forty years after thia\nIt' waa purchased by Claiidge, and\ntwo years ago It waa amalgamated\nwith the Savoy Hotel, Limited. Hun\ndred! of famous peape have been Its\nguosts. and hundreds of distinguish\ned men and women of the present\nday 'will gather tonight to celebrate\nMs centennial. All of the other ho\ntels will be the sceno of fashionable\nparties, and tho streets will be\nthronged .with nicrry-makeri through\nout the night.\nNo Favor, for Clergy.\nHieclU to Dally Panhandle.\n'Chicago, Dec. 31. The half fare\npermits of between 75.000 and 100,\n000 clergymen, Issued by western\nrailroads, expire today and will not\nbe renewed. After midnight tonight\nnot a alngle clergyman certificate\nwill be Issued by any railroad be\ntween Chicago and he Rocky Moun\ntains, with the possible exception ot\na few roads in Louisiana and Tex\nan. The Transcontinental Passen\nger association will continue to is\nsue blTf-rVa inwrntie to clergymen,\nto long as the passenger rates are\nnot reduced In the state of Colorado,\nMontana, Arizona and the state\n\"west to the Pacific coast.\ni The withdrawal of the clergymen's\nrates, which necessitated tho main\ntenance of expensive clergy bureau,\nwill reduce the expense of the West\nern Passenger asuoctttlon almost TS\nper cent and will make the expense\neem wit&ln. 159,090 a year.\nThe action of th railroads It In\nline with the announced policy of\nwithdrawing all reduced rate nrtrll\nees In spates where 3 cent fare law\nMr beea p'aitsed by tae lecmlature.\nMISS MAJUiOLLVS nECITAL.\nViolin PupJU Render Program at\nlleandl.\nBefore a select audience at the\nDeandi theater estcr(lay afternoon,\ntho more advanced pupils of MIhs\nHsther Margolin gave a violin, re\ndial and tho effort and ability\nshown by the pupil should by Varry\ngratifying to both their teacher and\nthemselves. Miss Margolin has had\ncharge of 'none of tho pupils over\ntwo month but tbo quality of the\nmusic selected and the excellence of\ntheir work 1a an earnest of the pos-\nslWlltleg of tho class. The piano\naccompaniment by Mrs. Ons Hollan\nder contributed much 1o their uc\ncess of the solo numbers.\nWith 'plesrlng graeo anj delK-jw y\nMiss Ruth Bloomhar gave first a\nPolonaise ''by Alleh. Schubert's\n,Troumerei,, aa a duet by Ml\"M Mar\ngolin and Miss Mary Weymouth was\nebe next number, Miss Weymottth\nwas beard to better advantage how\never, in net' solo; an l'dyll by Oodard,\nlater In Wie program. IiU San\nders dellgltted the auflienco with. the\nstrength an( character of ni pay\ning In the Tirth Aria from Charles\nDuncla, A number which showed\nthe progress the pupils have made\nIn concert playing was the minuet\nby O. Zanger which Misses Blootp\nhart, WeytiKiiith ud Margolin and\nMr. Sander' Wvertis n qnartetfe.\nMiss Mary Tlloomhart, in a duet with\nMis Margolin. Vlose the pupils pro\ngram wtth I'ettlte Symphonies from\nCharles Panda. a\nOn aeunt of hreatcnd' bone\nfelon. Miss Margolin played under\ndisadvantage end was obliged to omit\nthn numbers which the audience had\nhoped to hear from lier. As the last\nnumber, 'however, she gave the mel\nody of \"My Old Kentucky Hom\"\nwith variations In a way that brought\nher enthusiast! applause,\nROMB IS STOCK FXCHAXC.K,\nEighteen Persons Injured In Rome\nby Dynamiter.\nAmelated Presi. k\nRome,' Dec. 31. A dynamito\nbomb exploded In the stock exchange\nfn thl city today. Eighteen pers