over the\nWashington home of Senator Davis\nIn I street. Since the death c-f ihls\nwife five years ago Senator Davis\nhas divided his time botween this,\nbis former hflme, and the residence\nof hla son-in-law and daughter1. Mr.\nand Mrs. !e on Massachusetts ave\nnue. He always spends the wimmer\nmonths on his West Vlrg1nla\"tate,\nwhere Miss Ashford ten a: gnwt for\nfive weeks last eean;.\"- '1\nThat the aged imlllloflrfiw was\nfond of the Bociery- of brtlrttftU wo\nmen was shown Mst serfsoricblf the\nattentions 1 paid to many: peomi\nnent women, among the number be\nlng Mrs. Daniel Manning t Troy,\nX. Y., and Mrs, P. II. Hastings, wid\now of ex-governor Hayings of Penn\nsylvania. Hla name 'has never be\nfore been coupled with a woman so\nmuch his Junior as Miss Ashford,\nwho Is less than half his age.\nIt Is stated that by an arrange,\nment, mutually agreed npon the for\ntune of Senator Davis, estimated at\nfrom twenty-five to thirty millions,\nwill be divided 'In a manner agree\nable to his children and grandchil\ndren and the bride-to-be.\nThe children of Senator Davie are\nMrs. Elklns, Mrs. Lee and John T.\nDavis. Mrs. Elklns has four sons\nand one 'daughter; Mrs. Lee has\nfour children, the1 eldest 7 year of\nage, while Mr. and Mrs. John T.\nDavis have only one thtld. a little\ngiTl. Another prospective helresst to\nthe west Virginian's millions is Miss\nKatherine Davis Brown, only daugh\nter f the late Commander R. M. G.\nBrown.' U. 8. Nr, whose deceased\nwife was a daughter of the ex-fcen-ator.,\nr\nChurch Law In Algeria.\nSpecial to Dally Panhandle.\nratis. Dec. 31. Another vltrollc\nverbal warefarc between French of\nficials nnd the defenders of Cathol\nicism Is presaged on tho eve of the\nluforcement of the law separating\nchurch and slate In Algeria, which\nbecomes effective tomorrow. The de.\nore follows closely the terms of the\nFrench law on the subject, but will\nhave a wider latitude in1 its applica\ntion! as the government, recognizes\nthe Importance of the civilizing work\naccomplished by the missions in\nnorthern Africa. 'r1\nThe new law places Catholics. Pro\ntestants, Jews and jfilnelrt'aat in Al\ngeria on an equal footing. If cul\ntural association are formed,' the\nCatbollca may retain their church\nproperty and the trgy will enjoy\nthe benefit of .jen!on, Just as they\ncould bave fcn In Trance,1 had not\nthe vatlcal forbade the acceptance\nof the decree by Catholics. It Is re\nported that the pope ins ordered\nAlgerian Catholic, to ignore the U\nand this may lead to trouble between\n(he officials and th clergy.\nThe cost of maintaining th\" Mo.\nhammedan mosques, which the\nFrench government assumed the\ntime of the conquest of Alegria, munt\nbe born( ipy the .Muhechnans after\ntomorrow.\nx\nr.\nWest Virginia Lawyers.\nSpecial to Dally panhandle..\nNew Martinsville, W. Vs., Doc. .11.\nLegal I ghis from all. the oitlc\nand town of. Wed Virginia assem\nbled here loday for the twenty-third\nannual mooting, of tho Slato Bar\nhoclatlon. The annual address of the\nfptihlnnn will be delivered (((night by\nHon, William\" Herbert Phrc of Co\nlumbus, llilo. The convention 'I\"\ncloiie with a banquet tomorrow u:jrbt.\nTho address of the president. J. 'Hop\nWoods, 'dealt with \"'Involution in the\nLaw of Opinions.,':, Other speakers\non tho program Include p, J t'rn-\ngan on 'llablU and t ostumes or\nRench afid II r\"i W. W. Hushes on\n'Our System of Forfeiting Land\nTtltlcs.\" pud Charles McCamle on\nThe JuHtlce of the Peace; What\nIs the Remedy?\" 1\nA TRAMP AM) A HKRO.\nThis in, rank. here.,y,we know.lt.\nbut we wunt to go on jeeord right\nhere as 'doing homage to a ragged\nunkempt ,tramp and regardless of\nanv opinion to the contrary to say\nwe consider him one to whom hom\nage Is duo.'-'' v\nThe tramp was down In New Jer\nsey, where th'ey often chase tramps\nlth dogs, it was cold nd sleety.\nThe haystack In which he had slept\nfor the night was covered wlih snow\nand the w-lnd was to keen that the\ndogs sought